#Alan & Nora - R2 Cloudflare storage overview


Purpose: Create two completely separate storage spaces so different personal content areas remain independent and never mixed.

1Ô∏è‚É£ Buckets Created

Two R2 buckets are used:

family-archive

private-archive

Both buckets:

Must remain Private

Are fully independent

Do not share a global ‚ÄúAll Media‚Äù view

Provide emotional + contextual separation

2Ô∏è‚É£ Recommended Folder Structure

(Optional but helpful long-term)

Inside family-archive

/photos

/videos

/documents

/events

Inside private-archive

/photos

/videos

/secure

This ensures clarity and order as storage grows.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Manage Access (API Token)

Purpose: allow uploads (including very large files) and future automation.

Steps:

Go to Cloudflare R2

Open Manage Access

Create API Token

Permissions required:

Object Read

Object Write

Restrict token to:

family-archive

private-archive

Save token securely

No public access is enabled.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Uploading Files

Option A ‚Äî Normal uploads

R2 ‚Üí select bucket ‚Üí Upload

Option B ‚Äî Very large files (recommended for 4GB+)

rclone

or AWS CLI (R2 is S3-compatible)

This avoids browser timeout limits.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Benefits of This Design

Clear separation between life areas

No single ‚Äúall media everywhere‚Äù view

Handles huge video files easily

Private by default and secure

Low-cost storage that scales

Safe foundation for integrating into the private website later

6Ô∏è‚É£ Notes

Nothing here is public by default

Only accessible via Cloudflare account or API token

Website will reference this storage later when ready

Design is future-proof and long-term maintainable


# Alan & Nora ‚Äì Web + Private Portal Overview

This file exists to help me (Alan) remember:
- what systems I set up
- what things cost
- how to shut it ALL down if needed
- why things are structured the way they are

This is meant to protect my brain, my time, and my money.

---

## ‚ö†Ô∏è FINANCIAL & COMMITMENT CONTROL
### If I ever want to **stop all costs completely**, here is the checklist.

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ Cancel WordPress Hosting (Hostinger)
This is currently the only thing that regularly costs money.
- Log into Hostinger
- Go to **Billing / Subscriptions**
- Cancel the WordPress hosting plan
- This will remove:  
  `private.alanandnora.com` ‚≠ê

üëâ Cancelling Hostinger stops ALL *paid* hosting costs.

Nothing else is currently charging monthly.

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ Domain Name Renewal
The `alanandnora.com` domain renews annually.
If I want to stop paying even for the domain:
- Log into my domain registrar (Cloudflare or wherever I bought it)
- Turn off **auto-renew**
- Let it expire if I ever choose to

üëâ If I still want the name, I can just keep paying the yearly domain fee.

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Cloudflare
Cloudflare is currently **free plan**.
- If Hostinger is cancelled, Cloudflare will cost **$0**
- I can leave Cloudflare running forever with no charge

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Future Storage (NOT Active Yet)
If one day I add:
- Cloudflare R2
- Backblaze B2
- AWS S3

Then:
- Those are pay-as-you-go
- I can cancel/delete buckets any time to stop billing

---

## üí≥ What Might Be Charging My Card?
Right now, the potential or active charges in this project are:

- Hostinger WordPress hosting  
  ‚Üí yearly prepay / discounted promo / renews higher unless cancelled  

- Domain registration (`alanandnora.com`)  
  ‚Üí yearly renewal fee

Cloudflare Pages = **$0**
Cloudflare DNS = **$0**
GitHub = **$0**
WordPress software = **$0**

üìå Future-Me Rule:
If I ever feel overwhelmed, I can cancel Hostinger and keep only the domain + public website.  
That returns costs to almost nothing.

